Change has been successfully merged
The Jenkins error is due to the same unrelated error within an upstream library that is also blocking the https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/smbios-mdr/+/66452 change.
The Jenkins error is due to the same unrelated error within an upstream library that is also blocking the https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/smbios-mdr/+/66452 change.
sdbusplus::object_path instead?
I thought about that, but the class is written to prefer `std::string` usage, and I wanted to minimize the amount of refactoring. Also, `std::string` is well-understood and easy to work with.
const std::string&
I am using `std::move` to move them, and a reference can't be safely moved.
what's the benefits of copy -> move compared to reference -> copy?
This says it better than I can: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51705967/advantages-of-pass-by-value-and-stdmove-over-pass-by-reference
const std::string&
As above, I am using `std::move` on that string, so it can't be a ref.
std::formt?

Using `std::format` was my first choice, but the compiler/linker couldn't find it, interestingly enough, so I had to fall back to `fmt::fmt` which worked. Also, I did not want to change this code here, because upstream did it a certain way, and I wanted to avoid making changes that would deviate from the way upstream was doing things unless there was a tangible benefit in doing so.

wouldn't that just mean that your local env is not up to date?

Do you have gcc13 support when you build?

We are moving to std::fmt for the repos and slowly dropping the dependencies on the fmt lib, this repo was just not updated yet.
That's good to know. When we have std::format ready here, I can change it to use the new syntax. I also didn't want to rock the boat by introducing any new requirements, as this is refactoring only.
std::format
See above.
std::format?
See above.

I also added some weak_ptr through the callbacks, instead of just using "this", as a step towards getting this class to be able to destruct and construct again cleanly, without having to restart the process.
Jenkins still blocked on the same library error, unrelated to this change.
Why multiple MDRV2 is needed? Is this for multi-host use cases? Please explain

Yes. In this case, I have more than one host, attached to the same BMC. What happens here is that I need to have multiple copies of the SMBIOS blobs arrive, one from each host. Both sets of created SMBIOS objects need to coexist on D-Bus at the same time. To do this, many singletons must be changed, such as hardcoded object paths.
Can you show example of the objectPath used and dbus interfaces created as a result? This would help other people to use this feature.
I will add this as a GitHub Gist, as it is too large for a commit message.
Removed spammy logging message left in by accident from earlier testing. Still blocked on Jenkins `unpackArgs` library error.
can we call this getInterfaceFromObjectPath or something similar that describe the intend here?
Changed the name. I thought the intent was clear, to decide upon a place to put the GetRecordType interface, but perhaps not.

Reread the code and realized this is for GetRecordType interface only. I agree what you had probably is better than what I proposed here. If you want to change it back, I am fine with it. Sorry about that.
Thanks, no problem. I have changed back the name.
Why this change?

Good catch! Removed the extra return, it is not necessary. It was there because I had earlier added a debugging line below the if-block, which I have since cleaned up and turned into a rather helpful message now.
nit: Refactor
Made it more imperative!

Glad I tested. I cleaned up a bug in which the Associations were not established, because it couldn't find the way back to the anchor Inventory object in Entity Manager, to hang the newly arriving SMBIOS content off of.
Code change looks good to me. Leave it up for couple more days to see if there is any additional comment from other reviewer.
It has been a week, no more comments. Merge it now
